#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"The usual way of obtaining connections to a database is to use a datasource and configure a JDBC driver.\n"
"But you might also prefer using a reactive driver to connect to your database in a reactive way."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Agroal is a modern, lightweight connection pool implementation designed for very high performance and scalability,\n"
"and features first class integration with the other components in Quarkus, such as security, transaction management components, health, and metrics."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"This guide is mainly about datasource configuration.\n"
"If you want more details about how to consume and make use of a reactive datasource,\n"
"please refer to the xref:reactive-sql-clients.adoc[Reactive SQL clients guide]."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"This is a quick introduction to datasource configuration.\n"
"If you want a better understanding of how all this works, this guide has a lot more information in the subsequent paragraphs."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"When testing or running in dev mode Quarkus can even provide you with a zero config database out of the box, a feature\n"
"we refer to as Dev Services. Depending on your database type you may need Docker installed in order to use this feature."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"If you want to use Dev Services then all you need to do is include the relevant extension for the type of database you want,\n"
"e.g. `jdbc-postgresql`, `reactive-pg-client` or both. Don't configure a database URL, username and password -\n"
"Quarkus will provide the database and you can just start coding without worrying about config."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"If you only have a single JDBC extension, or you are running tests and only have a single test scoped JDBC extension installed then this is\n"
"optional. If there is only one possible extension we assume this is the correct one, and if a driver has been added with test scope then\n"
"we assume that this should be used in testing."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Add the correct reactive extension for the database you are using:\n"
"`reactive-db2-client`, `reactive-mssql-client`, `reactive-mysql-client`, `reactive-oracle-client`, or `reactive-pg-client`."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"A datasource can be either a JDBC datasource, a reactive one or both.\n"
"It all depends on how you configure it and which extensions you added to your project."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"To define a datasource, start with the following (note that this is only required if you have more than one\n"
"database type installed):"
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Giving Quarkus the database kind you are targeting will facilitate configuration.\n"
"By using a JDBC driver extension and setting the kind in the configuration,\n"
"Quarkus resolves the JDBC driver automatically,\n"
"so you don't need to configure it yourself.\n"
"If you want to use a database kind that is not part of the built-in ones, use `other` and define the JDBC driver explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"You can use any JDBC driver in a Quarkus app in JVM mode (see <<other-databases,Using other databases>>).\n"
"It is unlikely that it will work when compiling your application to a native executable though."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"JDBC is the most common database connection pattern.\n"
"You typically need a JDBC datasource when using Hibernate ORM."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Agroal comes as a transitive dependency of the Hibernate ORM extension so if you are using Hibernate ORM,\n"
"you don't need to add the Agroal extension dependency explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"The H2 and Derby databases can normally be configured to run in \"embedded mode\";\n"
"the extension does not support compiling the embedded database engine into native executables."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Note the `jdbc` prefix in the property name.\n"
"All the configuration properties specific to JDBC have this prefix."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"As previously stated, most of the time, this automatic resolution will suit you and\n"
"you won't need to configure the driver."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"You can use a specific driver if you need to (for instance for using the OpenTracing driver)\n"
"or if you want to use a database for which Quarkus does not have a built-in JDBC driver extension."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Without an extension, the driver will work fine in any Quarkus app running in JVM mode.\n"
"It is unlikely that it will work when compiling your application to a native executable though.\n"
"If you plan to make a native executable, we recommend you use the existing JDBC Quarkus extensions (or contribute one for your driver)."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"In the above example, the type is `AgroalDataSource` which is a subtype of `javax.sql.DataSource`.\n"
"Because of this, you can also use `javax.sql.DataSource` as the injected type."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"By default, if you include both a JDBC extension (+ Agroal) and a reactive datasource extension handling the given database kind,\n"
"both will be created."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"For now, multiple datasources are only supported for JDBC and the Agroal extension.\n"
"So it is not currently possible to create multiple reactive datasources."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"The Hibernate ORM extension xref:hibernate-orm.adoc#multiple-persistence-units[supports defining several persistence units using configuration properties].\n"
"For each persistence unit, you can point to the datasource of your choice."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Defining multiple datasources works exactly the same way as defining a single datasource, with one important change:\n"
"you define a name."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Notice there is an extra bit in the key.\n"
"The syntax is as follows: `quarkus.datasource.[optional name.][datasource property]`."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Even when only one database extension is installed, named databases need to specify at least one build time\n"
"property so that Quarkus knows they exist. Generally this will be the `db-kind` property, although you can also\n"
"specify Dev Services properties to create named datasources (covered later in this guide)."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"When using multiple datasources, each `DataSource` also has the `io.quarkus.agroal.DataSource` qualifier with the name of the datasource as the value.\n"
"Using the above properties to configure three different datasources, you can also inject each one as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"If you are using the `quarkus-smallrye-health` extension, the `quarkus-agroal` and reactive client extensions will automatically add a readiness health check\n"
"to validate the datasource."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"When you access the `/q/health/ready` endpoint of your application you will have information about the datasource validation status.\n"
"If you have multiple datasources, all datasources will be checked and the status will be `DOWN` as soon as there is one datasource validation failure."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"If you are using the `quarkus-micrometer` or `quarkus-smallrye-metrics` extension, `quarkus-agroal` can expose some data source metrics on the\n"
"`/q/metrics` endpoint. This can be turned on by setting the property `quarkus.datasource.metrics.enabled` to true."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"For the exposed metrics to contain any actual values, it is necessary that metric collection is enabled internally\n"
"by Agroal mechanisms. By default, this metric collection mechanism gets turned on for all data sources if a metrics extension\n"
"is present and metrics for the Agroal extension are enabled. If you want to disable metrics for a particular data source,\n"
"this can be done by setting `quarkus.datasource.jdbc.enable-metrics` to `false` (or `quarkus.datasource.<datasource name>.jdbc.enable-metrics` for a named datasource).\n"
"This disables collecting the metrics as well as exposing them in the `/q/metrics` endpoint,\n"
"because it does not make sense to expose metrics if the mechanism to collect them is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Conversely, setting `quarkus.datasource.jdbc.enable-metrics` to `true` (or `quarkus.datasource.<datasource name>.jdbc.enable-metrics` for a named datasource) explicitly can be used to enable collection of metrics even if\n"
"a metrics extension is not in use.\n"
"This can be useful if you need to access the collected metrics programmatically.\n"
"They are available after calling `dataSource.getMetrics()` on an injected `AgroalDataSource` instance. If collection of metrics is disabled\n"
"for this data source, all values will be zero."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"When using Dev Services the default datasource will always be created, but to specify a named datasource you need to have\n"
"at least one build time property so Quarkus knows to create the datasource. You will usually either specify\n"
"the `db-kind` property, or explicitly enable Dev Services: `quarkus.datasource.\"name\".devservices.enabled=true`."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"Our suggestion is to use the real database you intend to use in production; container technologies made this simple enough so you no longer have an excuse. Still, there are sometimes\n"
"good reasons to also want the ability to run quick integration tests using the JVM powered databases,\n"
"so this is possible as well."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"It is important to remember that when configuring H2 (or Derby) to use the embedded engine,\n"
"this will work as usual in JVM mode but such an application will not compile into a native executable, as the Quarkus extensions only cover for making the JDBC client code compatible with the native compilation step: embedding the whole database engine into a native executable is currently not implemented."
msgstr ""

#: /home/ynojima/playground/ja.quarkus.io/build/jekyll-source/_versions/2.13/guides/datasource.adoc
msgid ""
"This will allow you to test your application even when it's compiled into a native executable,\n"
"while the database will run in the JVM as usual."
msgstr ""

